    <text>
    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Horace</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I must write one line to say how deeply I rejoice that the affair is over, &amp; that my dear Ida has borne it so well.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> God bless her.</p>
<p>Your affectionate Father | Charles Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. Whenever George calls, give him the enclosed.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1227.xml">Ida Darwin</ref> had given birth to her first child, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_9337.xml">Erasmus Darwin</ref> (1881–1915), on 7 December (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2662.xml">Freeman 1978</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The enclosure for <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml">George Howard Darwin</ref> has not been found, but see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13532.xml">letter from G. H. Darwin, [6 December 1881]</ref>. </note>      
        </div>   
       
